{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-03043/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-03043"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:30:43"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["medium shot"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["low"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["fixed"]}},{"label":{"none":["Lighting"]},"value":{"none":["low key"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["single shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A woman sits cross-legged on a chair with a notebook."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03043/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-03043","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03043/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-03043"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03043/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03043/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03043/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03043/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03043/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03043/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03043/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03043/canvas/1/6a58a59b-77e6-490a-bc9a-6c16ac314350","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T20:45:19.200Z","creator":"g","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Cyril’s cruelty on full display. The siblings have a deep bond, so her jealousy reveals itself quickly. This line is drawn from Mary Blume’s biography of designer Cristóbal Balenciaga: “The women he really liked to dress, French or not, were oddly enough small, plump, and middle-aged—Mme Bizcarrando, Mme Maeght, Mme Kandinsky, the widow of the painter, Mme Zumsteg, and Janine Janet, his window dresser. They were part of his experiments in sculpting form: ‘Monsieur likes a bit of belly’ was the saying in the house” (Blume, <em>The Master of Us All</em>, 150). Catherine Join-Diéterle also reports this detail: “It is said of him that he liked a bit of stomach; just as with Zubarán’s female saints, this stomach was the source of the tilted line that recurs in his dresses and suits from 1952 onward” (Join-Diéterle, “Dior and Balenciaga,” 150).&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03043/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:436.7160161507403,184.03768506056534,540.0807537012112,394.07806191117095"}}}]}]}]}